<article id="post-3015" class="post-3015 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-general category-renovations">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2012/03/kitchen-renovation-day-8/" rel="bookmark">Kitchen renovation, day 8</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<a class="post-thumbnail" href="http://geoff.wp/2012/03/kitchen-renovation-day-8/" aria-hidden="true">
			</a>

		
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Just over a week ago, our kitchen officially went out of commission. Today, it looks oh-so close to being functional once again. Considering the short period of time, and some of the challenges that have come up, I&#8217;m rather amazed at the progress (and pleased with the results thus far).<br />
At the same time, I&#8217;m starting to get worried. I can see what remains. I know how things tend to get rushed towards the ends of projects, and how corners get cut. I know how things can go from &#8220;good&#8221; to &#8220;okay&#8221; to &#8220;terrible&#8221; in a shockingly short period of time.<br />
I&#8217;m hoping I&#8217;m way, way wrong.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2012/03/kitchen-renovation-day-8/#more-3015" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Kitchen renovation, day 8&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	<footer class="entry-footer">
